a111 8
During the process of strong collaboration, each participant is
contributing to the construction of the artifact, and gaining new knowledge
as a direct result of this construction.  The constructed artifact is not
simply a patchwork of individual contributions, but instead, an
incremental, emergent synthesis that reflects the knowledge created by the
group as a whole.  In general, strong collaboration most often (though not
always) occurs in non-computer mediated, face-to-face contexts such as a
group software design session or an interactive classroom setting.
d113 4
a116 11
Strong collaboration is at one end of a collaborative spectrum.  The other
end of the spectrum is the traditional divide and conquer method of
collaborating.  We call the divide and conquer method weak collaboration
since there is very little interaction between the participants.  In weak
collaboration, each participant works on their own section of the artifact
independently.  When all of the sections are finished the artifact is
created by combining the sections into a whole.  A distinguishing
characteristic of weak collaboration is distinct ownership of the sections.
Each section can be directly attributed to a participant.  A characteristic
of strong collaboration is group ownership of the sections.  Each section
can not be directly attributed to a single participant.
d118 4
a121 9
Computational support for weak collaboration is well established.  Word
processors can import different artifacts to create a new artifact.  E-mail
can send different sections of the artifact across the globe to other
contributors.  The World Wide Web is essentially a collection of
independently authored artifacts.  However, the computational needs of
strong collaboration are not well understood.  So, we designed AEN to
explore computer support of strong collaboration in the creation of
hypertext documents.  In order to support strong collaboration AEN must
also support weak collaboration.  
