In order to help detect %define
strong collaboration, we created an operationalized
d123 2
a124 2
component of the definition.  The following is our operationalized
definition and corresponding metric for strong collaboration:
a125 5
\begin{enumerate}
\item{\em Members read each other's nodes.}  Strong collaboration requires
  that the members of the group know the current state of the artifact.
  Without reading the other nodes members have no way of contributing to
  the nodes.
d127 4
a130 2
  {\bf Metric:} {\em Readers per node (RPN)}.  This metric measures the
  number of readers per node.  
d132 2
a133 35
\item{\em Members edit nodes that were also edited by others.}  This
  is the most direct way that members can collaborate on a node.  One author
  creates a node, then another author adds to it.

  {\bf Metric:} {\em Member Co-editing (MCE)}.  This metric measures the
  number of members that each member co-edits with.
 
\item{\em Document nodes are edited by more than one person.}  This
  operationalization ensures that there is interaction among the group
  members for each node.  Without this interaction the node is created in a
  weakly collaborative way.

  {\bf Metric:} {\em Editors per node (EPN)}.  This metric measures the
  number of editors per node.

\item{\em Members create feedback nodes.}  This is another way for group
  members to collaborate.  They can create feedback on the contents of a
  node.

  {\bf Metric:} {\em Feedback Node Creation (FNC)}.  This metric measures
  the number of feedback nodes created by each member.

\item{\em Members manipulate access control to publish/protect artifacts
  under development.}  By changing the access control members are able to
  dynamically control the process of collaboration.

  {\bf Metric:} {\em Non-default Access Control (NAC)} and {\em Evolving
  Access Control (EAC)}.  These metrics measure two different features of
  access control.  NAC measures if the node's access control has changed
  from the default and EAC measures if then node's access control has
  evolved over the life of the node.
\end{enumerate}

The data collected shows that, accross all of the groups, each of the
metrics had at least one instace that scored high.  This implies that AEN
