With the rapid expansion of the World Wide Web \cite{Berners-Lee94} more
authors are writing hypertext documents.  The WWW has allowed more
of us to collaborate.  The issues of collaborating to develop hypertext
documents are becoming more and more important each day.  The use of
hypertext as a structuring mechanism for richly interdependent information
is becoming more widespread, and finds application in many areas of
software engineering and other fields.
d37 6
a42 3
Unfortunately, the WWW provides little support for collaboratively authoring
hypertext document.  So to explore collaboration in authoring and learning we
had to implement our own collaborative hypertext authoring/learning tool.
d44 10
a53 7
AEN\footnote{Annotated Egret Navigator} is built upon Egret
\cite{csdl-93-09} a client-server hypertext database manager.
Authors/learners use AEN's typed nodes and links to give the hypertext
document structure.  They also use an access control model to dynamically
restrict the type of access to the individual nodes in the database.
Several autonomous agents help AEN manage all of the information needed to
support strong collaboration.
d55 8
a62 12
Strong collaboration is the opposite of the traditional divide and conquer
method of collaborating.  Each participant works on their own portion of
the artifact independently.  When all of the portions are finished the
artifact is created by combining the portions into a whole.  We call this
divide and conquer method weak collaboration since there is very little
interaction between the participants.  One of the key characteristics of
weak collaboration is distinct ownership of the portions.  Each portion can
be directly attributed to a participant.  Computational support for weak
collaboration is well established.  Word processors can import different
artifacts to create a new artifact.  E-mail can send different portions of
the artifact across the globe to other contributors.  The World Wide Web is
essentially a collection of independently authored artifacts.
d64 11
a74 12
In strong collaboration, each participant contributes to each portion as it
is being developed.  During the process of strong collaboration, each
participant is contributing to the construction of the artifact, and
gaining new knowledge as a direct result of this construction.  The
constructed artifact is not simply a patchwork of individual contributions,
but instead, an incremental, emergent synthesis that reflects the knowledge
created by the group as a whole.  In general, strong collaboration most
often (though not always) occurs in non-computer mediated, face-to-face
contexts such as a group software design session or an interactive
classroom setting.  The computational needs of strong collaboration are not
well understood.  We designed AEN to explore computer support of strong
collaboration.
d76 9
a84 1
\section{Initial Experiences}
d86 3
d90 1
a90 7
Over the past year, we have experimented with and redesigned AEN, a reader
and authoring system for hypertext, that places equal weight on supporting
the following, collaborative authoring of, and collecting data about user
interaction with, a hypertext document.  A third requirement of the system
is rapid response time. This system and our ideas about collaboration have
undergone extensive evolution as we learned more about the implications of
these requirements and their often conflicting natures.
d92 4
a95 9
It took three months to take AEN from a simple set of requirements to the
first prototype.  We came up with a simple hypertext authoring tool that
allows multiple authors to edit different nodes of the same hypertext
document at the same time.  In the Fall of 1994 we used the initial
prototype in a graduate seminar class ICS 691.  The class used AEN and it's
database as the text book and example of a collaborative system.  During
the semester the students found bugs in AEN and made over 28 suggestions
about improving AEN.  We redesigned and made AEN more robust.  During the
Fall semester we developed the concept of strong collaboration.
d97 18
a114 6
We hoped that the Fall, 1994 ICS 691 class would demonstrate strong
collaboration. However, due to problems with the reliability of AEN, they
lost faith with AEN and did not use it for collaboration. The students
learned that AEN could not be trusted to keep all of their work.  They
began using alternative methods to collaborate and just uploaded the
results to AEN for grading.
a115 28

\section{Experimental design and results}

Since we were unable to detect strong collaboration during the fall of
1994, we decided to conduct an experimental case study during the spring of
1995.  Three groups in an undergraduate class in software engineering used
AEN to develop their requirements documents.  Each group consisted of five
students.  They worked with private companies developing software products
for the companies.  The groups learned how to use software engineering
principles to develop their software products.

In order to detect strong collaboration within the groups we have
operationalized strong collaboration into the following operations:
\begin{itemize}
\item{Members create feedback nodes.}
\item{Members read each other's nodes.}  
\item{Each member edits nodes that were also edited by others.}
\item{All document nodes are edited by more than one person.}  
\item{Authors concurrently edit the same document node.}
\item{If team members are simultaneously logged in, Partyline is used.}
\item{A majority of members find the Snoopy and Partyline features for
  physical presence to be useful.}
\item{Members manipulate access control to publish/protect artifacts
  under development.}  
\item{All nodes underwent manipulation of access control.}
\end{itemize}


